{You have a very solid 17 points and a balanced hand. You open 1NT. Partner responds 3NT and you pass.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \HJ. You hopefully put on the \HQ, but North plays the \HK.

<b>East plays 3NT. South leads the \HJ. You hopefully put on the \HQ, but North plays the \HK.</b>

Winners: \S 0 : \H 1 : \D 1 : \C 4 : Total = 6

A hold-up won't help unless North had a doubleton \H, giving South a 7-card suit. So you win your \HA. The \S suit is solid after the \SA is played, but before you could enjoy those 3 tricks the defenders would have really enjoyed a bunch of \Hs.

Your only hope is to win 8 more tricks before you lose the lead. That means the \D finesse had better work. At trick 2 you lead your \DQ, playing low from dummy if South doesn't cover. Repeat the finesse as necessary. When South has the \DK you will make your contract, and when North has the \DK you will go down. That's a 50% chance, just like most finesses. But remember, if you had tried to establish the \S suit instead of taking the finesse your chance of making 3NT would be 0%.

You can see what could have happened if you had tried to sneak even one \S trick. North would have grabbed the \SA and played a small \H. South would have happily taken 4 \H tricks and you would be down 1.}
[Play "W"]HJ

